<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-01-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="437" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                        <head>437. Telegram 1351 from Geneva<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d437fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Files,
                                611.93/1–1156. Confidential; Priority.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-01-11">January 11, 1956, 11
                                    a.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <pb facs="d437-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d437-1"/>
                        <p>1351. From <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>. Re Deptel
                            1467.</p>
                        <p>Would appreciate prior tomorrow’s meeting text any statement by INS re
                            Liu and substance American Red Cross reply to Madame Li.</p>
                        <p>Would also appreciate any info that would assist me in answering probable
                            question as to why nothing happened re Liu’s case between attempted
                            deportation 11951 when he presumably able travel and date <persName corresp="#p_WP_1">Wang</persName>’s letter.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GFC_1"><hi rend="strong">Gowen</hi></persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>